patient recovers quickly.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anaphylaxis","Hypotensive transfusion reaction","Transfusion-associated circulatory overload","Acute haemolytic transfusion reaction","Transfusion-associated lung injury"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypotensive transfusion reactions\u003C/strong\u003E present as a sudden decrease in blood pressure of at least 30 mmHg typically within the first 15 minutes of a transfusion and responds rapidly to the cessation of transfusion and supportive care. It is caused by the production of bradykinin produced through Factor XII activation by negatively charged surfaces such as filters. When mechanisms for the degradation of bradykinin are impaired, the peptide builds up and causes hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaphylactic transfusion reactions \u003C/strong\u003Eare characterised by an acute onset of hypotension, early in the transfusion. Other symptoms that are typical of an allergic reaction can also be present, including urticaria and pruritus, laryngeal oedema, and respiratory tract obstruction leading to difficulty breathing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfusion-related acute lung injury \u003C/strong\u003Emanifests as sudden onset of severe dyspnoea, hypoxia, and the development of diffuse pulmonary infiltrates. This typically takes place within one to six hours following the beginning of the transfusion but is typically not immediate. Also, fever and hypotension, although can be present, are minor components of the reaction. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute haemolytic transfusion reactions \u003C/strong\u003Edue to the transfusion of incompatible red blood cells, hypotension is not the initial symptom and appears later in the course of the reaction, after the activation of various biologic response cascades. Before hypotension manifests, other symptoms such as nausea and vomiting, back pain, fever, chills, haematuria, and other signs of haemolysis are present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Isolated hypotensive transfusion reactions typically occur \u003C 15 minutes after the start of the transfusion and respond rapidly to the cessation of transfusion and supportive care."],"references":["Bruno DS, Herman JH. Acute Hypotensive Transfusion Reactions. Laboratory Medicine. 2006;37(9):542-5. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/labmed/article/37/9/542/2657487"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28673"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11856"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28673"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-25T13:09:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-25T13:09:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4456"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43666"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":n